Epizootic haemorrhagic disease, Tunisia
---------------------------------------
Information received on [and dated] 1 Oct 2015 from Dr Malek Zrelli, directeur general, Direction Generale des Services Veterinaires, Ministere de l'Agriculture, Tunis, Tunisia

Summary
Report type: immediate notification
Date of confirmation of the event: 11 Sep 2015
Reason for notification: reoccurrence of a listed disease
Date of previous occurrence: 15 Nov 2006
Manifestation of disease: clinical disease
Causal agent: epizootic haemorrhagic disease virus
Nature of diagnosis: clinical, laboratory (advanced)
This event pertains to a defined zone within the country

New outbreaks (1)
Summary of outbreaks
Total outbreaks: 1
Outbreak 1: Oued Beja Nord, Sidi Alouane, Mahdia
Date of start of the outbreak: 11 Sep 2015
Outbreak status: continuing (or date resolved not provided)
Epidemiological unit: farm
Affected animals:
Species / Susceptible / Cases / Deaths / Destroyed / Slaughtered
Cattle/ 5 / 4 / 0 / 0 / 0
Affected population: Sick animals are older than 3 years and they showed salivation, ocular lesions (keratitis and watering) and diarrhoea.
Outbreak statistics [rates apparent, expressed as percentages]:
Species / Morbidity rate / Mortality rate / Case fatality rate / Proportion susceptible animals lost*
Rabbits / 80 / 0 / 0 / 0
*Removed from the susceptible population through death, destruction and/or slaughter

Epidemiology
Source of the outbreak(s) or origin of infection: unknown or inconclusive
Epidemiological comment: In addition to the listed control measures biosecurity measures have been strengthened.

Control measures
Measures applied: dipping/spraying, surveillance within containment and/or protection zone; control of vectors; no vaccination; treatment of affected animals (eye drops)
Measures to be applied: no other measures

Diagnostic test results
Laboratory name and type / Species / Test / Test date / Result
Veterinary Research Institute, Tunisia (National Laboratory) / Cattle / real-time PCR / 22 Sep 2015 / Positive

Future reporting
The event is continuing. Weekly follow-up reports will be submitted.

